1
00:00:01,482 --> 00:00:20,065
namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha-sambudassam namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha-sambudassam

2
00:00:20,045 --> 00:00:39,628
Namo dasa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:39,648 --> 00:00:48,499
I like to start like that just to remind me that I'm supposed to be teaching what the Buddha taught, in case I slip in with my own little bits.

4
00:00:49,271 --> 00:00:54,860
Just to go through an evening like this and to understand what we're trying to do.

5
00:00:54,881 --> 00:01:04,114
When we bow, for instance, so if you look at any religious form, it always has some form of bowing.

6
00:01:06,278 --> 00:01:09,102
The Muslims bow from the waist, there are all sorts of things.

7
00:01:10,248 --> 00:01:12,855
the Hindus bow, Christians genuflect.

8
00:01:13,677 --> 00:01:26,129
So there's something about a physical action of bowing, which is, what its main purpose is, that surrender.

9
00:01:26,802 --> 00:01:27,683
See?

10
00:01:27,703 --> 00:01:56,269
When you actually bow, whenever you, whenever, if you just watch yourself with people whom you consider to be slightly above you, have power over you, your boss or whatever, you'll see, whether you like it or not, your position changes, your shoulders lower, you tend to try to lower yourself, your voice softens, and all these little indications which we as Westerners, because of our

11
00:01:56,248 --> 00:02:05,504
our deep individualism and equality don't like to show, but actually it's just there, it's just manifest.

12
00:02:06,486 --> 00:02:13,598
So the idea of any spiritual path is a surrender to that path.

13
00:02:14,139 --> 00:02:21,312
And the reason why all these religions have a physical representation of it is because

14
00:02:21,292 --> 00:02:26,260
whatever spiritual path we're on, it'll always ask us to do exactly what we don't want to do.

15
00:02:26,281 --> 00:02:34,836
I mean, the whole point is to go against desire, the self, its selfishness and all that sort of stuff.

16
00:02:35,637 --> 00:02:37,419
And we don't want to do that.

17
00:02:37,961 --> 00:02:45,274
So any spiritual path worthy of its name will always ask us to do things that we simply don't want to do.

18
00:02:46,418 --> 00:02:51,574
And that action of bowing is a surrender to that, it's a yielding.

19
00:02:52,417 --> 00:02:56,530
It's saying, you know, well, whatever has to be done, that has to be done.

20
00:02:57,995 --> 00:03:04,084
That's one of these little pat phrases that comes up in the scriptures when somebody becomes fully liberated.

21
00:03:04,443 --> 00:03:07,429
They always say, what had to be done has been done.

22
00:03:08,751 --> 00:03:12,616
And what this takes us to is a different understanding about free will.

23
00:03:13,296 --> 00:03:27,478
Free will is really a delusion about somebody having a choice and that choice is somehow an expression of my free will to do what I want.

24
00:03:28,133 --> 00:03:29,974
But as we know, everything is conditioned.

25
00:03:32,998 --> 00:03:47,298
So this idea of some sort of individual that's floating around the place, completely separate from the universe, who can make decisions, totally, you know, it's just ridiculous.

26
00:03:49,501 --> 00:03:53,145
The spiritual path doesn't give you a choice.

27
00:03:53,986 --> 00:03:57,972
Whenever choice arises on the spiritual path, it arises because of confusion.

28
00:03:58,643 --> 00:04:00,064
It's a bit like going for a walk.

29
00:04:00,344 --> 00:04:06,895
When you take out your map and you think, well, I'll walk up here and I'll go up, you know, St. Brendan's Hill and all that sort of stuff, there's the path.

30
00:04:06,914 --> 00:04:10,259
So you get to a place where there's suddenly a crossroad and you don't know where you're going.

31
00:04:10,599 --> 00:04:11,461
So what do you do?

32
00:04:11,861 --> 00:04:13,724
You don't make a choice.

33
00:04:13,745 --> 00:04:16,488
You take out your map and you look at it and you think, well, this is the way.

34
00:04:17,430 --> 00:04:19,052
So it's the same with the spiritual path.

35
00:04:19,173 --> 00:04:24,240
You can presume that whenever there's a choice coming up, it's usually a point of confusion.

36
00:04:25,461 --> 00:04:25,562
Okay?

37
00:04:27,701 --> 00:04:35,771
Even in ordinary life, whenever you're presented with a choice, should I do that job or that job, should I pick this tin of beans or that tin of beans, it's confusing.

38
00:04:36,593 --> 00:04:39,295
It's just there because you don't know.

39
00:04:39,315 --> 00:04:41,499
And we don't like being in a place of don't know.

40
00:04:42,240 --> 00:04:44,622
So we tend to make rash judgments.

41
00:04:44,642 --> 00:04:51,630
But the point about the bowing in any of these religions is that commitment, you see.

42
00:04:52,451 --> 00:04:55,755
Being open to being told what to do.

43
00:04:56,377 --> 00:04:57,338
That's the point.

44
00:04:58,482 --> 00:05:05,449
And I failed to light the lamp which was put out there especially so I would light it.

45
00:05:05,468 --> 00:05:23,966
It was unfortunate really because light, the flame, is the universal spiritual symbol because of its light which symbolizes the path of understanding, the path of investigation, the heat, the path of love, and its action, the path of doing, the path of action.

46
00:05:23,947 --> 00:05:29,165
So those are your three paths and they are expressed through the Eightfold Noble Path.

47
00:05:29,185 --> 00:05:33,720
So one starts the Eightfold Noble Path by trying to understand the way things really are.

48
00:05:34,240 --> 00:05:40,889
And what this means is to begin to see things from the enlightened person's point of view, from the awakened person's point of view.

49
00:05:41,529 --> 00:05:49,040
And that is to constantly awaken that way of looking, of seeing that everything arises and passes away.

50
00:05:49,100 --> 00:05:55,488
Now that's pretty obvious when you look outside yourself and sometimes it's pretty obvious when you look in the mirror.

51
00:05:55,468 --> 00:06:05,620
But it's when you go internally to this idea of a self, you see, and you just have to contemplate certain things like, well, when I go to sleep, I disappear.

52
00:06:06,841 --> 00:06:08,744
The alarm goes and here I am.

53
00:06:09,904 --> 00:06:11,165
So, where have I been?

54
00:06:11,206 --> 00:06:13,048
Where have I been these past eight hours?

55
00:06:13,108 --> 00:06:15,011
And that's loss of self there, you see.

56
00:06:15,350 --> 00:06:18,894
Now, if a doctor said to you, if you fall asleep,

57
00:06:19,312 --> 00:06:20,454
you will definitely die.

58
00:06:22,158 --> 00:06:28,427
You're going to pin your eyelids to your forehead to make sure that you do not fall asleep.

59
00:06:29,269 --> 00:06:37,103
So the only reason that we fall asleep in that sense of peace is that we presume that the I will arise again in the morning.

60
00:06:42,533 --> 00:06:46,117
So the other thing is to understand the doctrine of not-self.

61
00:06:46,197 --> 00:06:47,358
That's a bit more subtle.

62
00:06:47,418 --> 00:06:50,322
But remember, the Buddha never saying that there is no self.

63
00:06:50,403 --> 00:06:52,045
It's not a metaphysical statement.

64
00:06:52,084 --> 00:06:53,887
It's not about who we really are.

65
00:06:54,769 --> 00:06:59,394
The whole teaching of not-self is to be able to point at something and say, well, this is not me, not mine.

66
00:06:59,875 --> 00:07:05,081
And that takes us to the meditation, which we can go into a little bit more deeply in a minute.

67
00:07:05,062 --> 00:07:09,867
And the other thing is to understand this quality of where does suffering arise.

68
00:07:10,749 --> 00:07:15,374
Psychologically speaking, it lies around that quality of desire, desire of attachment.

69
00:07:16,836 --> 00:07:22,262
So when we see these things in the right view, you see, there's a change of attitude.

70
00:07:23,184 --> 00:07:29,971
And that attitude, which is based on a self, must necessarily always be attentive to the needs of the self.

71
00:07:30,833 --> 00:07:33,516
And what the self needs at base is safety.

72
00:07:33,495 --> 00:07:34,759
It needs to feel safe.

73
00:07:34,839 --> 00:07:38,449
If you don't feel safe, then you feel very anxious, very fearful.

74
00:07:39,110 --> 00:07:41,516
So our lives are about making ourselves feel safe.

75
00:07:42,478 --> 00:07:46,009
The warm hearth, the food on the table, the insurance policy.

76
00:07:46,870 --> 00:07:47,612
Even for the grave.

77
00:07:49,076 --> 00:07:50,339
Make sure you get a decent grave.

78
00:07:52,327 --> 00:08:02,012
My father, towards the end of his life, took out a special £2,000 mortgage to make sure that he got a decent amount of stuff.

79
00:08:02,052 --> 00:08:05,983
I still feel guilty about that because he didn't spend it all on his grave.

80
00:08:07,009 --> 00:08:13,682
So, the case of safety, and to make ourselves feel safe, then of course we have to accumulate.

81
00:08:13,721 --> 00:08:17,629
The more we accumulate, the more we feel safe, and hence we move into greed.

82
00:08:18,451 --> 00:08:20,494
Greed, accumulation, all that sort of stuff.

83
00:08:20,935 --> 00:08:24,781
And that takes us into, at worst, criminality.

84
00:08:25,387 --> 00:08:35,620
And because we need to feel that safety, because we've accumulated these things, then of course we have to guard it against those who might rip it off us, and hence aversion arises.

85
00:08:36,480 --> 00:08:45,592
And when that attacker, when that person or society or group feels as though they've got the better of us, then we have to run for it.

86
00:08:46,212 --> 00:08:50,719
So we're into the next stage of our psychology, which is just aversion and fear.

87
00:08:52,014 --> 00:09:03,936
And from that, of course, comes all the secondary stuff around shame, guilt, remorse, we push things away and get depressed, and so on and so forth.

88
00:09:04,496 --> 00:09:09,905
But the self, you see, once it's been established, it has to have that base of safety.

89
00:09:10,121 --> 00:09:19,773
And the fact of the matter is that no matter how much it accumulates, it never feels, it cannot feel utterly safe, because it knows that it arises and passes away.

90
00:09:20,875 --> 00:09:21,655
So it's a fact.

91
00:09:23,057 --> 00:09:27,903
So these three ways of looking at things begin to change our attitude.

92
00:09:27,982 --> 00:09:31,287
So our attitude moves from selfishness,

93
00:09:31,267 --> 00:09:39,501
As the selfishness disappears, the self-centeredness, safety, then of course it turns outwards and it moves towards generosity.

94
00:09:40,203 --> 00:09:41,245
It's a natural movement.

95
00:09:41,986 --> 00:09:44,993
Where once we felt aversion, we feel love.

96
00:09:45,153 --> 00:09:48,499
Where once we practice cruelty, we begin to feel compassion.

97
00:09:49,052 --> 00:10:00,792
So the heart, you see, sometimes you get the feeling that what Buddhism is about is moving towards almost the state of a cold stone, because basically it's all about investigation.

98
00:10:01,232 --> 00:10:04,597
But the Buddha heart is there for us to read.

99
00:10:04,577 --> 00:10:08,663
He's quite open about his emotional states, about the mental states that he's in.

100
00:10:08,682 --> 00:10:14,269
He says he's happy when people take on the Dhamma, take on his teaching, but he's not unhappy when people don't.

101
00:10:15,951 --> 00:10:27,403
And he says constantly, he says, whatever a teacher can do for his students out of compassion, anukampa, and that word anukampa means moving towards the other.

102
00:10:27,764 --> 00:10:30,687
It's an actual action, moving towards the other.

103
00:10:30,667 --> 00:10:37,797
And whatever a teacher has done out of compassion for his students, I have done for you.

104
00:10:38,618 --> 00:10:46,889
So it would be wrong to think that the Buddha went around with some sort of equanimous indifferent heart that didn't actually connect with people.

105
00:10:47,110 --> 00:10:50,215
Far from it.

106
00:10:50,235 --> 00:10:54,961
And then once the attitude changes within us, it has to express itself.

107
00:10:55,042 --> 00:10:57,424
So attitudes need to express themselves.

108
00:10:58,086 --> 00:11:00,048
If you don't, you just become a vegetable.

109
00:11:00,907 --> 00:11:05,591
And it expresses itself through right speech, right action, right livelihood.

110
00:11:05,611 --> 00:11:11,558
So our language changes, our actions change, and what we do with our lives becomes important.

111
00:11:15,302 --> 00:11:19,508
So all that is prefigured, you see, in the Eightfold Noble Path.

112
00:11:19,607 --> 00:11:25,934
The flame, the light, the warmth and the action is right there in the Noble Eightfold Path.

113
00:11:26,741 --> 00:11:30,365
And that brings us to the reason for ritual.

114
00:11:30,586 --> 00:11:37,774
So ritual is just that moment where we actually do something which is symbolic of our spiritual life.

115
00:11:38,655 --> 00:11:47,667
So the lighting of the candle, the bowing, and then praising or bringing to mind the quality of the spiritual leader.

116
00:11:48,006 --> 00:11:53,913
So here we acknowledge the Buddha as somebody who said he was fully self-enlightened,

117
00:11:54,518 --> 00:12:02,730
and that he had worked towards it by himself, and that we have a relationship to that historical figure.

118
00:12:04,394 --> 00:12:13,908
It may be a relationship of just one other teacher, somebody whom we refer to, or it could be that that is our central archetype, the very exemplar of our own life.

119
00:12:15,191 --> 00:12:18,956
So it depends where you put that historical personage.

120
00:12:18,937 --> 00:12:28,186
If you look at all these scriptures, if you look at all these religions, the people who follow that leader are simply following that same lifestyle.

121
00:12:29,427 --> 00:12:34,410
So the life of love and sacrifice would be a Christian approach.

122
00:12:35,052 --> 00:12:39,735
The life of insight and compassion would be the Buddhist approach.

123
00:12:39,975 --> 00:12:48,183
So all these paths have a particular view of how to get to the top of the spiritual mountain.

124
00:12:48,974 --> 00:12:57,466
So having praised the qualities of the archetype of the Buddha, one then begins to take refuge.

125
00:12:57,647 --> 00:13:00,311
So the refuge is in the Buddha, the Dharma and the Sangha.

126
00:13:01,251 --> 00:13:08,383
And we take it three times because that's an ancient habit of making sure that you actually mean what you say.

127
00:13:08,363 --> 00:13:18,104
So in the scriptures when somebody asks a question of the Buddha and he says no, they always ask it three times to make sure that he actually means it.

128
00:13:18,124 --> 00:13:21,851
So he said you take this refuge in the Buddha Dhamma Sangha.

129
00:13:21,951 --> 00:13:24,717
So the Buddha here for people who are...

130
00:13:24,697 --> 00:13:52,038
born Buddhists, cultural Buddhists this always refers to some historical figure but for those who are into the actual spiritual path what you're taking refuge in is the Buddha within there's something which in us has to be awakened and unless you have an inkling of that unless you have some sort of small faith in that then it undermines the whole practice there has to be that understanding that what we're trying to do is awaken something inside us

131
00:13:53,115 --> 00:13:58,721
And the Dhamma is that teaching, here specifically the meditation that we're doing.

132
00:13:58,937 --> 00:14:15,321
And the Sangha refers to, in the religion, to all those people who've experienced some form of enlightenment, so that we're taking refuge in people who actually have had this same experience.

133
00:14:15,341 --> 00:14:17,583
But for us, as practitioners, it's each other.

134
00:14:18,225 --> 00:14:27,577
And because you recognize, you begin to realize that actually, unless you're with a group, unless you're with people around you who are going the same way, it's very difficult.

135
00:14:28,115 --> 00:14:28,777
very difficult.

136
00:14:29,418 --> 00:14:36,394
Just to come here and make that effort once a week through the hail, rain and snow, you know, to come to a meeting is an act of will.

137
00:14:36,835 --> 00:14:39,441
And that act of will is a commitment to the path.

138
00:14:39,943 --> 00:14:45,129
And just to come here once a week and practice has an effect on your weekly practice.

139
00:14:45,149 --> 00:14:48,493
I know all this from my own personal experience.

140
00:14:48,552 --> 00:14:55,240
Just to make my way across Birmingham, come hail, rain or shine, it had an effect.

141
00:14:55,440 --> 00:15:00,706
And if I laid off it, if I didn't go a couple of weeks, it would revert back to my morning practice.

142
00:15:00,725 --> 00:15:01,527
It's as simple as that.

143
00:15:02,687 --> 00:15:07,493
And what we're doing by making that effort is strengthening that commitment, strengthening that will.

144
00:15:07,513 --> 00:15:09,495
And that reverberates through the rest of our lives.

145
00:15:10,909 --> 00:15:31,769
So then, having taken the refuges and precepts, and that little blessing I gave, it just simply says, you know, that we've taken the refuges and precepts, and then it leaves you with the final exhortation of the Buddha, which is to practice diligently for our own liberation.

146
00:15:32,240 --> 00:15:35,345
Then we come to the actual practice, so the practice itself.

147
00:15:36,226 --> 00:15:37,148
What is that, you see?

148
00:15:37,528 --> 00:15:38,711
Well, we're trying to find out.

149
00:15:38,730 --> 00:15:50,711
We're trying to find an observation post within ourselves, some sort of position where we can actually observe this psychophysical organism that sort of wanders around the world calling itself me.

150
00:15:51,812 --> 00:15:52,433
See?

151
00:15:52,453 --> 00:15:54,657
And you want to know when you get that position.

152
00:15:54,677 --> 00:15:56,340
So this is a very...

153
00:15:58,159 --> 00:15:59,981
It's a very exceptional position.

154
00:16:00,222 --> 00:16:04,648
You really can't do this if you're walking around and in action.

155
00:16:05,229 --> 00:16:13,839
In the sitting posture, it is specific about finding this position where you can feel sensations and you can actually investigate them.

156
00:16:14,200 --> 00:16:17,143
You can investigate your relationship to those sensations.

157
00:16:17,243 --> 00:16:19,025
If it's pleasant, how you want to indulge it.

158
00:16:19,105 --> 00:16:21,028
If it's unpleasant, how you want to turn away from it.

159
00:16:21,700 --> 00:16:30,131
In this position, you can actually begin to feel an emotion as something not me, not mine, rather than saying, I am depressed.

160
00:16:30,152 --> 00:16:31,554
You say, there is depression.

161
00:16:31,615 --> 00:16:33,778
You point to it there.

162
00:16:33,798 --> 00:16:46,596
And it's by making that inner world as objective to yourself as the outer world is objective, which begins to abstract, disembed that which in us, which is the Buddha nature.

163
00:16:47,217 --> 00:16:50,863
And that Buddha nature is simply the one who knows.

164
00:16:51,907 --> 00:17:09,492
And as you begin to see thoughts as arising and passing away, distance, not me, not mine, emotions arising and passing away, distance, not me, not mine, feelings in the body arising and passing away, distance, as not me, not mine, you're then thrown back to this feeling of being the observer.

165
00:17:10,064 --> 00:17:21,376
But that feeling of the observer, remember, is also a distortion, because it's the self, it's that intelligence catching its own presence within the atmosphere, within the mirror of the mind itself.

166
00:17:22,597 --> 00:17:24,359
So I liken it to watching television.

167
00:17:24,519 --> 00:17:31,647
When you watch television, sometimes your image is in the screen, so now you can decide, are you going to watch yourself watching television, or are you going to watch television?

168
00:17:32,650 --> 00:17:38,316
And if you keep concentrating on the television, that sense of a self disappears.

169
00:17:38,296 --> 00:17:51,270
So in your meditation, even though you might feel that very strong sense of being the observer, the witness, the one who feels, the one who knows, keep putting your attention on what it is you're actually trying to investigate.

170
00:17:52,271 --> 00:17:59,140
And every so often you might just experience just the disappearance of the knower, the observer.

171
00:17:59,660 --> 00:18:03,324
So there's a collapse of that which knows into what it knows.

172
00:18:03,484 --> 00:18:06,548
And that, in a sense, is your pure vipassana.

173
00:18:06,528 --> 00:18:09,371
It's only at that point that we can talk about pure vipassana.

174
00:18:09,811 --> 00:18:22,747
Not that insights can't come before that, that's fine, but it's only at that point that we can begin to experience things at a level which truly begin to turn the way we see things.

175
00:18:22,866 --> 00:18:34,340
So that's the point of the practice, and that's why we need to do it morning and evening especially, because in the morning we have to set ourselves to that way of being in the world.

176
00:18:34,522 --> 00:18:42,394
You have to remind yourself that you must keep that sense of awareness of what I'm doing from the time I get up to the time I fall asleep.

177
00:18:43,496 --> 00:18:45,818
And in the evening it's important.

178
00:18:45,959 --> 00:18:50,746
Best done, you know, when we come back from work, have a cup of tea or something and relax.

179
00:18:50,806 --> 00:18:52,448
Not when you go to bed, you just fall asleep.

180
00:18:53,368 --> 00:18:58,876
It's a case of sitting there and just seeing what we've accumulated during the day.

181
00:18:58,856 --> 00:19:07,457
Any tensions, any irritations, whatever we've accumulated, we sit there and we just wait for it to pass.

182
00:19:08,057 --> 00:19:15,394
And then we acknowledge these have arisen because during the day I've lost that moment to moment life on earth.

183
00:19:15,454 --> 00:19:17,118
And then you normally have a decent evening.

184
00:19:19,933 --> 00:19:23,602
Then finally, there has to be this metta, this goodwill.

185
00:19:23,721 --> 00:19:29,753
So the purpose of that is to remind us that we are drawing this intelligence into the heart.

186
00:19:30,695 --> 00:19:39,914
And that change of attitude will come naturally with the growth of wisdom, but we can definitely help the process by practicing this loving-kindness, you see.

187
00:19:40,395 --> 00:19:41,317
And then...

188
00:19:41,298 --> 00:19:45,882
By bringing people to mind, there's that reconnecting with the world.

189
00:19:45,942 --> 00:19:55,070
If you don't do that, this meditation can have the effect of you remaining too aloof and people feel that you're distant from them.

190
00:19:55,090 --> 00:19:55,872
So you have to be careful.

191
00:19:55,892 --> 00:19:58,474
You have to bring it into the heart and reconnect with people.

192
00:19:58,914 --> 00:20:04,780
And in so doing, you then remind yourself that you're actually also doing this for the benefit of all beings.

193
00:20:05,181 --> 00:20:06,883
When you change, the world changes.

194
00:20:07,943 --> 00:20:09,144
Not immediately, of course.

195
00:20:10,001 --> 00:20:11,403
So that's the whole idea, you see.

196
00:20:11,784 --> 00:20:14,826
So that connection is made in your meditation, you see.

197
00:20:14,987 --> 00:20:30,284
So we're moving from that inward gaze, the inward understanding, then an attitude out into the world, and when we rise from the seat, it should express itself in the way we speak, and what we do, and in the livelihood that we choose to follow.

198
00:20:33,007 --> 00:20:33,106
Yeah.

199
00:20:48,307 --> 00:20:48,808
Yeah, that's it.

200
00:20:51,854 --> 00:20:52,134
Easy.

201
00:20:52,815 --> 00:20:53,576
Easy, easy peasy.

202
00:21:01,348 --> 00:21:10,703
When you talk about bringing the intellect into the heart and bringing mental, what exactly do you mean by heart?

203
00:21:11,003 --> 00:21:13,387
Ah, just your emotional life.

204
00:21:14,481 --> 00:21:16,689
Your warmth, your feelings, your...

205
00:21:17,010 --> 00:21:23,834
I mean, it includes all, everything that you would normally describe as emotions, moods, mental states.

206
00:21:25,980 --> 00:21:27,224
But they would be around...

207
00:21:27,509 --> 00:21:49,534
Well, it depends, you know, we split, I mean on one end of the scale there are the thinkers, who think their emotions are up in their head, and on the other end you get the feelers, who think their thoughts are actually in the heart.

208
00:21:49,884 --> 00:21:57,102
And it depends where you are on the scale of things as to what you have to do.

209
00:21:59,768 --> 00:22:00,670
Generally speaking.

210
00:22:01,191 --> 00:22:02,815
That's what I'm saying.

211
00:22:04,701 --> 00:22:23,431
Well, I think, I would say, you know, I know that some people, for some people, such is their block in thinking, that they actually think they feel their emotions up here.

212
00:22:24,753 --> 00:22:27,317
Yeah?

213
00:22:27,557 --> 00:22:27,637
Yes.

214
00:22:29,625 --> 00:22:35,257
I don't think it matters where you actually feel the emotion as long as you understand that that is an emotion.

215
00:22:36,920 --> 00:22:43,010
But I think as you begin to meditate and that separation of thought comes from the emotional base,

216
00:22:43,395 --> 00:22:47,000
then it's here that you feel emotion.

217
00:22:47,039 --> 00:22:48,842
This is the exchange box for emotions.

218
00:22:48,882 --> 00:22:56,010
I mean, you might feel nausea, or you might feel tightness in the stomach, but you're only guessing that it's anxiety.

219
00:22:56,211 --> 00:23:00,236
It's only when anxiety rises into the heart that you know, oops, I am actually anxious.

220
00:23:01,857 --> 00:23:04,881
As a mood, as a felt emotion.

221
00:23:07,290 --> 00:23:13,400
So we know that certain parts of the body tend to hold emotions for us that we've suppressed out of consciousness.

222
00:23:15,022 --> 00:23:22,574
And often in our meditation what we think is actual physical pain is none other than an emotion trying to release itself.

223
00:23:24,215 --> 00:23:32,808
And often if that emotion has been deeply suppressed it needs to come out as a physical feeling and you never know really what the emotion was.

224
00:23:35,438 --> 00:23:46,711
So, for instance, pain in the neck, headaches, pain in the back, stomach pain, chest pain, gub is all sorts.

225
00:23:47,872 --> 00:23:49,453
And sometimes you don't know.

226
00:23:49,493 --> 00:23:56,320
You don't know what it was.

227
00:23:56,602 --> 00:24:02,407
What I'm saying may be silly, but when I'm meditating and

228
00:24:03,046 --> 00:24:06,951
See, normally the attention is turned on the breathing.

229
00:24:07,813 --> 00:24:15,223
But I also heard about turning the attention away from the breathing and on to mind, the nature of the mind.

230
00:24:16,384 --> 00:24:19,329
Sorry, turn away from the breathing and?

231
00:24:20,090 --> 00:24:20,892
Turn it out.

232
00:24:21,132 --> 00:24:21,972
The nature of the mind.

233
00:24:21,992 --> 00:24:23,756
Understanding the nature of mind.

234
00:24:25,238 --> 00:24:27,882
Just dwelling on that, possibly.

235
00:24:27,902 --> 00:24:32,749
But when I do that, okay, there's something, mind there, all right, but

236
00:24:33,083 --> 00:24:36,086
right there in front of me, or somewhere in my head, out of the front.

237
00:24:36,807 --> 00:24:41,991
I seem to have this blood, this ball of tangled rope, or something like that.

238
00:24:43,353 --> 00:24:54,864
It's there, and if I let my mind rest on that, and I can more easily than on my breath, I can keep it there.

239
00:24:55,865 --> 00:24:57,747
And sometimes my body begins to twitch.

240
00:24:58,988 --> 00:25:00,609
I don't know what it's all about.

241
00:25:00,893 --> 00:25:11,462
Could it be, because you just said something about some people feel their emotions in their head, is it something related to that?

242
00:25:12,804 --> 00:25:17,148
When you say a ball of string, are you saying that's an actual image that you see?

243
00:25:17,429 --> 00:25:22,354
It's almost tangible.

244
00:25:22,374 --> 00:25:26,917
It feels like something inside my head or inside in the area that I'm...

245
00:25:27,369 --> 00:25:30,375
Observing.

246
00:25:30,394 --> 00:25:33,922
It's quite distinguishing.

247
00:25:39,471 --> 00:25:43,699
I suppose it feels a bit too like a ball of tantrum.

248
00:25:44,760 --> 00:25:45,682
Ball of tantrum.

249
00:25:49,375 --> 00:26:03,048
what's important is to know the relationship between the mind with its thoughts and images and stories and what's motivating them, which is these emotions, these emotional base.

250
00:26:08,973 --> 00:26:19,263
In the Wheel of Dependent Origination, which is the psychology of the Buddha, it's called that, he points out that

251
00:26:20,257 --> 00:26:25,884
At the point of contact, consciousness arises and awareness arises of something.

252
00:26:26,846 --> 00:26:41,846
That contact is either physical, something we see or hear, it's emotional, coming out from the heart, or it's something that touches the mind, a thought, an image.

253
00:26:43,970 --> 00:26:49,217
As soon as you've got that contact, that basic percept,

254
00:26:50,632 --> 00:26:56,559
perception arises for it to be either pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

255
00:27:00,064 --> 00:27:10,136
At that next point there is a grabbing of that object in terms of either indulging it, pushing it away or ignoring it.

256
00:27:11,858 --> 00:27:15,182
Now, how do we indulge an emotion?

257
00:27:16,664 --> 00:27:18,968
How do we indulge an emotion?

258
00:27:20,045 --> 00:27:21,426
It's through the head, isn't it?

259
00:27:23,170 --> 00:27:27,557
There's a feeling of irritation comes and before you know it you're arguing with somebody in your head.

260
00:27:28,858 --> 00:27:32,003
You're feeling depressed and there you are walking to the bridge.

261
00:27:33,145 --> 00:27:33,445
You see?

262
00:27:33,646 --> 00:27:34,567
It's all in the head.

263
00:27:36,191 --> 00:27:44,584
When you begin to recognize the connection between what we do in our heads and what we do in our emotions, you cut your head off.

264
00:27:46,740 --> 00:27:48,123
You really do.

265
00:27:48,143 --> 00:27:48,923
You cut your head off.

266
00:27:49,684 --> 00:27:53,830
And what you do is, as soon as a thought arises, you just cut it.

267
00:27:55,093 --> 00:27:55,693
Absolutely.

268
00:27:55,993 --> 00:27:56,355
Cut it.

269
00:27:57,557 --> 00:28:00,320
And any time an image or a film arises, you cut it.

270
00:28:00,840 --> 00:28:04,586
And you turn away from that to what is actually empowering those thoughts.

271
00:28:05,347 --> 00:28:09,614
And you always find it in the heart as a mental state or emotion.

272
00:28:09,634 --> 00:28:09,914
You see?

273
00:28:10,255 --> 00:28:14,181
I'm talking about all these things that are negative, by the way, and wholesome, yeah?

274
00:28:14,201 --> 00:28:14,300
Yeah.

275
00:28:15,461 --> 00:28:28,156
And when this emotion, when this state of mind, which is nothing but an energy form, and when you go into it, what is it that you actually experience depression as, or anxiety as, or anger as?

276
00:28:28,237 --> 00:28:36,445
What is the actual direct experience of that emotion as a felt state, not as a thought?

277
00:28:36,465 --> 00:28:38,989
You see, that's what you've got to discover.

278
00:28:39,711 --> 00:28:41,013
When you get down there, what do you feel?

279
00:28:41,035 --> 00:28:42,196
A bit of heat?

280
00:28:42,217 --> 00:28:43,057
A bit of pressure?

281
00:28:43,278 --> 00:28:43,819
Sensation?

282
00:28:44,361 --> 00:28:45,142
It's nothing at all.

283
00:28:46,684 --> 00:28:50,211
And we made such a big thing, didn't we?

284
00:28:50,231 --> 00:28:57,486
And when you can stay with that in a calm and sensible way like that, you see, where has that energy got to go?

285
00:28:57,526 --> 00:29:00,791
You can't go anywhere.

286
00:29:01,295 --> 00:29:03,678
It needs your empowerment for it to grow.

287
00:29:03,718 --> 00:29:07,321
And the way you empower it is by creating a fantasy around it.

288
00:29:07,602 --> 00:29:09,904
The fantasy feeds into it and it builds up.

289
00:29:10,404 --> 00:29:12,567
It's like you put your foot on the accelerator.

290
00:29:13,008 --> 00:29:14,650
If you take the accelerator, where does it go?

291
00:29:14,670 --> 00:29:16,011
It fizzles out, it goes out.

292
00:29:16,673 --> 00:29:20,297
So all these deep depressions, anxieties, eventually they all fizzle out.

293
00:29:20,317 --> 00:29:23,099
25, 50 years.

294
00:29:24,109 --> 00:29:32,059
I don't want to give you false hope, because this stuff is really empowered.

295
00:29:33,421 --> 00:29:44,654
Now, when you recognize that and you recognize the power of the mind and what it's actually doing, of course, every time you get a skillful thought, a wholesome thought, then you generate those thoughts.

296
00:29:44,674 --> 00:29:47,198
And that's what we're doing with the metta practice.

297
00:29:48,577 --> 00:30:00,751
So, if we feel something negative within us, you see, then whatever image the mind offers, you see, come off it, come off it, go into that state.

298
00:30:03,536 --> 00:30:04,376
You go into the state.

299
00:30:06,098 --> 00:30:13,547
If you put out what's in the mind, does it automatically go back into the heart center?

300
00:30:14,188 --> 00:30:16,611
No, you've got to put your attention there.

301
00:30:16,792 --> 00:30:27,411
You see, every time you put your attention on something, whether you like it or not, you've made an act of intention.

302
00:30:27,790 --> 00:30:32,179
Whatever you attend to is conditioning you.

303
00:30:33,140 --> 00:30:37,567
So even going along the car and you see a billboard and you look at it, you've conditioned yourself.

304
00:30:40,092 --> 00:30:43,257
You've always gotten by the same biscuits.

305
00:30:45,311 --> 00:30:57,967
And it's really understanding the power of attention and its conditions and how it conditions us that then you understand the Buddha's advice to restrain the senses.

306
00:30:59,229 --> 00:31:03,453
Not to look, not to listen to those things which you know are unwholesome.

307
00:31:04,174 --> 00:31:09,560
The restraint of the senses.

308
00:31:09,800 --> 00:31:11,242
It's so strong.

309
00:31:11,262 --> 00:31:14,626
Yeah.

310
00:31:14,928 --> 00:31:21,896
You start off at the beginning talking about choice and decision, and you're saying it's conditioned.

311
00:31:24,099 --> 00:31:31,068
I didn't quite understand that at the beginning, because, you know, surely you make choices.

312
00:31:32,150 --> 00:31:40,259
That's one of the only things you can really do as a human being, to be aware, to make a choice.

313
00:31:40,780 --> 00:31:41,761
Yes, absolutely.

314
00:31:42,583 --> 00:31:44,766
You have a choice, you make a decision,

315
00:31:45,623 --> 00:31:49,605
But the choice is always because of confusion, of not knowing.

316
00:31:49,665 --> 00:31:53,269
Unless you wouldn't have a choice, you wouldn't know what to do.

317
00:31:53,288 --> 00:31:56,811
See, if you get up in the morning and you know you have to go to work, you don't have a choice.

318
00:31:57,873 --> 00:32:00,355
You just go to work.

319
00:32:00,375 --> 00:32:01,316
Well, you think you do.

320
00:32:01,336 --> 00:32:03,097
Isn't it more subtle than that?

321
00:32:03,117 --> 00:32:05,799
Go on.

322
00:32:10,644 --> 00:32:15,208
You say, for instance, you have a choice.

323
00:32:17,685 --> 00:32:33,926
Maybe there is no confusion.

324
00:32:36,109 --> 00:32:39,835
Maybe you say, you know quite well.

325
00:32:39,875 --> 00:32:41,616
Oh, that's not a problem.

326
00:32:42,097 --> 00:32:46,343
Yeah, I mean... Then you can say, surely you can bring...

327
00:32:46,643 --> 00:33:04,550
that's not a problem but when you go into your reasons as to why you've chosen to do good rather than evil you'll find that those conditions were conditioned your reasons were conditioned and

328
00:33:07,365 --> 00:33:20,263
And the whole point of the practice is to begin to see clearly how every time we act from the base of an unskillful thought, an unwholesome thought, we actually create suffering for ourselves.

329
00:33:20,284 --> 00:33:21,125
It's a consequence.

330
00:33:21,506 --> 00:33:25,632
And every time we work from the basis of a skillful, wholesome thought, it actually makes us happy.

331
00:33:27,594 --> 00:33:28,516
And that's all we're doing.

332
00:33:29,297 --> 00:33:32,141
There's no mystery about it at all.

333
00:33:32,421 --> 00:33:33,863
It's just basic psychology.

334
00:33:36,761 --> 00:34:00,013
And remember what we're trying to do is to liberate, that's the word, liberate this quality, this essential quality we are from its delusive relationship with the body, mind and heart and the world it finds itself in.

335
00:34:04,661 --> 00:34:04,760
Okay?

336
00:34:05,887 --> 00:34:12,576
It would be difficult to teach very young children that kind of philosophy, wouldn't it?

337
00:34:12,956 --> 00:34:29,414
Well, the thing is with young children, little Fionn here, is it's all there as little seeds, it's dropping into his ears and it's there hanging around and at some point I'm sure he'll be fully liberated.

338
00:34:29,394 --> 00:34:37,427
But remember, for children, it's about doing good and all that sort of stuff.

339
00:34:37,467 --> 00:34:39,572
It's a usual thing that you would teach children, you know.

340
00:34:40,492 --> 00:34:43,538
I don't know if it's 25, 50 years, he's got a better chance than that.

341
00:34:43,557 --> 00:34:44,159
He has indeed.

342
00:34:45,041 --> 00:34:49,007
Definitely.

343
00:34:49,612 --> 00:34:58,382
If you were conditioned from a very young age to this kind of idea, it would be a great advantage, wouldn't it?

344
00:34:58,402 --> 00:34:59,242
Well, yes.

345
00:34:59,262 --> 00:35:00,643
Would that be able to take it in?

346
00:35:01,005 --> 00:35:02,246
Well, not necessarily.

347
00:35:02,505 --> 00:35:07,532
I mean, you know, you go to Buddhist countries and they're just as pathetic as we are.

348
00:35:09,653 --> 00:35:17,862
It's just that, you know, I mean, every religious tradition has its own wisdom and stuff, but there are other things going on, aren't there?

349
00:35:18,603 --> 00:35:30,333
So this, you see, just to go back to this business of choice, you see,

350
00:35:35,882 --> 00:35:43,371
If you, say tomorrow, you decide that you will note every time a choice comes into your head.

351
00:35:44,112 --> 00:35:45,514
Like, for instance, shall I have a cup of tea?

352
00:35:47,757 --> 00:35:47,878
Right?

353
00:35:47,898 --> 00:35:48,478
And you stop.

354
00:35:49,039 --> 00:35:51,882
And you go into that sense of choice.

355
00:35:52,063 --> 00:35:54,405
Will I have or will I not have a cup of tea?

356
00:35:54,927 --> 00:35:59,532
So as soon as you stay with it, you see, you'll find the man arguing for and against.

357
00:36:00,054 --> 00:36:01,215
For and against.

358
00:36:01,195 --> 00:36:30,492
and then you make a decision on one of these for or against you see now then you say to yourself well I had free will I could have chosen this but I didn't I chose that but you didn't this is the point you didn't choose the other one so therefore your choice inverted commas was conditioned by your own arguments do you see what I mean you can't you can't escape the conditioning of

359
00:36:30,625 --> 00:36:31,326
that you are.

360
00:36:32,106 --> 00:36:33,027
You see?

361
00:36:33,047 --> 00:36:39,432
So now, the self, you see, holds this wonderful position where it thinks that it has made a choice.

362
00:36:40,353 --> 00:36:44,677
Because at one point it had two things it could do, have a cup of tea or not have a cup of tea.

363
00:36:45,737 --> 00:36:51,682
And therefore it gets this lovely sense of itself being above the world and above conditioning.

364
00:36:52,324 --> 00:36:55,146
And it can do what it wants in its own time, in its own way.

365
00:36:56,126 --> 00:36:57,929
And that is one of the great delusions.

366
00:37:00,451 --> 00:37:00,530
See?

367
00:37:02,570 --> 00:37:04,512
Where is the larger encounter?

368
00:37:04,532 --> 00:37:04,913
Which one?

369
00:37:06,534 --> 00:37:07,996
Of the idea that you have choice.

370
00:37:08,938 --> 00:37:12,722
Well, it's actually, we have to blame St. Augustine for this.

371
00:37:14,864 --> 00:37:16,387
You see, it doesn't exist in the East.

372
00:37:16,588 --> 00:37:22,474
This idea of a free will does not exist in Hindu and Buddhist or in Chinese.

373
00:37:22,494 --> 00:37:24,958
How do they make a choice?

374
00:37:24,978 --> 00:37:25,639
There is no choice.

375
00:37:25,659 --> 00:37:26,619
It's karma.

376
00:37:26,954 --> 00:37:29,076
And what you do is, through your wisdom...

377
00:37:29,317 --> 00:37:35,123
If you make a choice or decision about, say, a career or a life option, how do they do something like that?

378
00:37:35,143 --> 00:37:37,365
Well, they'll think they were just conditioned to do it.

379
00:37:38,266 --> 00:37:45,655
And what they're trying to do is understand things so that it changes that conditioning and therefore changes their choosing.

380
00:37:46,235 --> 00:37:50,882
But they don't fall into this idea of free will.

381
00:37:52,423 --> 00:37:56,168
All acts that we make are determined.

382
00:37:56,570 --> 00:38:00,478
But isn't it just another way of saying the same thing, really?

383
00:38:00,778 --> 00:38:07,795
I know where you're coming from, but I think what she's saying is that basically Easterners have a different word for it.

384
00:38:08,432 --> 00:38:10,516
Whereas we call it free will, they call it karma.

385
00:38:11,097 --> 00:38:13,119
But in fact, the natural law cannot be broken.

386
00:38:13,139 --> 00:38:14,282
I think that's what you were saying.

387
00:38:14,543 --> 00:38:16,224
Basically, the natural law is there.

388
00:38:16,346 --> 00:38:21,213
And even if we think we're breaking it, or changing it, or doing something, we can't actually go against it.

389
00:38:21,233 --> 00:38:23,697
Because if we go against it, we'll end up in a negative place.

390
00:38:24,117 --> 00:38:25,960
We'll end up collecting all of that negative power.

391
00:38:26,342 --> 00:38:31,510
If we go in the positive direction, we'll accumulate the benefits, and so will everybody else.

392
00:38:31,530 --> 00:38:32,170
That's what I think.

393
00:38:34,014 --> 00:38:36,077
They're saying that we all have

394
00:38:41,947 --> 00:38:44,331
Well, no, it wouldn't be.

395
00:38:44,371 --> 00:38:47,476
You see, what can we say?

396
00:38:47,536 --> 00:38:52,507
The Buddhist position is not that we are essentially evil.

397
00:38:53,387 --> 00:38:56,012
There's a very different tack on life.

398
00:38:56,434 --> 00:39:01,744
Well, the Buddhist position is that we're essentially deluded, which is a very different position.

399
00:39:02,197 --> 00:39:08,106
And the delusion is entered because we come into life in a position of not knowing.

400
00:39:08,947 --> 00:39:16,179
So whether you want to believe in past lives or not, even in this life, what did you know in the womb?

401
00:39:18,862 --> 00:39:21,728
What did you know at birth, you see?

402
00:39:22,108 --> 00:39:24,552
So we come in in a state of not knowing.

403
00:39:25,173 --> 00:39:27,376
Now that not knowing is not culpable.

404
00:39:29,652 --> 00:39:31,934
You can't blame somebody for not knowing.

405
00:39:34,338 --> 00:39:38,304
So then from then on we are told what we should know.

406
00:39:39,487 --> 00:39:51,744
And then round about the age of 16, 17, 18 or something, for some people much earlier, they reflect on this and they begin to shake off those things that they've been conditioned with or they agree with it.

407
00:39:53,681 --> 00:40:03,117
In that not knowing, we fall into the error of thinking that this body, this person, this personality is me.

408
00:40:04,038 --> 00:40:12,992
And just as we described before, this leads us into safety, the problems of safety, the problems of accumulation, the problems of aversion, etc., etc.

409
00:40:13,353 --> 00:40:16,297
So evil and skillfulness is secondary.

410
00:40:17,340 --> 00:40:39,898
Now, what this means is that because evil is secondary and has been caused by a mistake, when you go back on the process and the mistake is undone, you find that that ignorance had in it an essential innocence, and therefore you can return to purity.

411
00:40:41,260 --> 00:40:43,804
If you were essentially evil, you couldn't do it.

412
00:40:45,909 --> 00:40:53,800
So, ignorance moves to wisdom, innocence returns to purity.

413
00:40:58,108 --> 00:41:12,188
What you've been saying, though, would also indicate that I'm not really fully able to make a decision

414
00:41:13,518 --> 00:41:16,001
say, for good or for evil.

415
00:41:16,021 --> 00:41:16,541
I don't know.

416
00:41:16,782 --> 00:41:19,346
Because I'm being conditioned.

417
00:41:19,365 --> 00:41:28,998
So I can always say, well, you know, when I took that money, that person was just conditioned.

418
00:41:29,880 --> 00:41:30,721
Yes, absolutely.

419
00:41:31,101 --> 00:41:36,748
It's one of these... Well, no, you see, that undermines the fact that there is also this intelligence.

420
00:41:37,369 --> 00:41:43,137
So although we are not essentially culpable for our...

421
00:41:43,824 --> 00:41:51,516
unskillfulness for our evil, we are paradoxically fully responsible for it.

422
00:41:51,536 --> 00:41:53,380
And that's the law of karma, you see.

423
00:41:53,780 --> 00:41:59,971
And there's no way you can undo the law of karma apart from suffering the consequences of your actions.

424
00:42:00,811 --> 00:42:06,440
Now, your actual karma is not something coming at you from the outside world.

425
00:42:06,909 --> 00:42:10,934
It's not the fact that you end up in prison or that you win the lottery, anything like that.

426
00:42:11,536 --> 00:42:13,559
Your karma is your mental state.

427
00:42:13,699 --> 00:42:17,364
When you sit like that, in your posture, that's your karma.

428
00:42:19,847 --> 00:42:22,550
Yeah, but can I say that I've inherited it?

429
00:42:24,233 --> 00:42:25,554
From?

430
00:42:25,574 --> 00:42:27,396
From the past, from past lives.

431
00:42:27,436 --> 00:42:28,378
Yeah, absolutely.

432
00:42:29,422 --> 00:42:35,568
What we're talking about is not thought, we're talking about attitudes.

433
00:42:35,929 --> 00:42:40,614
What you inherit from your past lives are your attitudes and understanding.

434
00:42:44,117 --> 00:42:52,387
Even in this life, you wake up in the morning and you're carrying the whole of this life into that morning.

435
00:42:54,489 --> 00:42:59,074
Only one part of it becomes part of your consciousness, but it's all there as potential.

436
00:43:01,518 --> 00:43:05,282
and given certain conditions, certain potentialities manifest.

437
00:43:11,891 --> 00:43:12,612
But you can change.

438
00:43:13,393 --> 00:43:20,983
Well, ultimately the idea is that you recognize that you've actually created this mind, you've created this personality.

439
00:43:22,605 --> 00:43:30,715
People have given you things, shall we say, people have given you material to work with, your language, your culture,

440
00:43:31,387 --> 00:43:35,057
But what you make of it, you discover, is totally you.

441
00:43:35,800 --> 00:43:40,114
That's why you can't blame anybody for your internal suffering.

442
00:43:41,123 --> 00:43:48,711
You have to give up the comfort of being able to blame your parents for all your misery and society.

443
00:43:49,333 --> 00:43:52,056
And it's all, it's us, we've done it, you see.

444
00:43:52,976 --> 00:44:06,152
And when you actually take full responsibility for this, then of course you begin to change it and you realise that the very things that, the little acts of internal will that you made which created these states can now be undone

445
00:44:06,132 --> 00:44:11,657
And you end up with a heart which you can then develop indefinitely.

446
00:44:12,159 --> 00:44:18,065
So love, compassion, joy and peace don't have a definite ending to them.

447
00:44:19,947 --> 00:44:23,070
They're difficult to say infinite, but indefinite.

448
00:44:23,291 --> 00:44:24,753
That's why they're called illimitables.

449
00:44:25,994 --> 00:44:27,335
These states are illimitable.

450
00:44:29,478 --> 00:44:31,820
Can I just ask you about the choice thing?

451
00:44:31,922 --> 00:44:33,202
What's the choice thing?

452
00:44:33,637 --> 00:44:39,545
I understand when people are making a choice about eating a cup of tea, or not a cup of tea, that's something you do in a split second.

453
00:44:40,146 --> 00:44:57,146
But when people are making even more serious choices, life-changing choices, whether they're moving home, whether they're moving country, whether they're moving jobs, that kind of thing, you know you were talking about all that to-ing and fro-ing and all the conditioning that goes on in people's minds, and sometimes people can take months to make decisions.

454
00:44:58,429 --> 00:45:03,594
But where... How do people come to that point then?

455
00:45:04,570 --> 00:45:06,692
of making a decision for either or?

456
00:45:07,293 --> 00:45:09,576
Well, I think sometimes it's because we lack information.

457
00:45:11,217 --> 00:45:12,177
Just simple information.

458
00:45:12,498 --> 00:45:17,143
And also because there is that lack of clarity in the heart as to what it actually wants to do.

459
00:45:18,304 --> 00:45:19,806
So often you have to just wait.

460
00:45:20,487 --> 00:45:29,998
I mean, just to take my personal experience, it took me two years to decide to robe, to leave the job and robe.

461
00:45:30,297 --> 00:45:31,860
And I struggled with it for one year.

462
00:45:32,447 --> 00:45:37,775
And when I went to see my teacher and said, Bhante, I said, I want to become a monk.

463
00:45:37,795 --> 00:45:38,577
He said, you're too old.

464
00:45:39,577 --> 00:45:40,960
And I felt an enormous relief.

465
00:45:43,362 --> 00:45:49,692
I thought, oh, that year in my head going around with lists and all that sort of stuff.

466
00:45:49,711 --> 00:45:56,802
And then I struggled with it a bit more and I went back and he gave me another excuse, something about he needed me at the Vihara because by then I was teaching and very involved.

467
00:45:57,523 --> 00:46:06,054
And then I went away and I spent two weeks by myself in Wales, in somebody's little cottage out there, and there just came that absolute certainty.

468
00:46:06,715 --> 00:46:07,476
It took two years.

469
00:46:08,998 --> 00:46:12,003
So it was from the heart then at that point and not from the head, really?

470
00:46:12,402 --> 00:46:15,027
Well, it was always coming from the heart, but the head was confused.

471
00:46:15,126 --> 00:46:16,027
Yeah, that's the point.

472
00:46:16,047 --> 00:46:16,929
Because of attachment.

473
00:46:17,228 --> 00:46:19,391
You see, you know, talk about head and heart, you know what I mean?

474
00:46:19,411 --> 00:46:24,679
I was attached to the way of life I was with and what it meant, selling the house and all that, you know, and there's all that and...

475
00:46:24,659 --> 00:46:26,603
And I knew it would be the end of the career as such.

476
00:46:26,724 --> 00:46:29,351
It's like a massive change, you see.

477
00:46:29,391 --> 00:46:32,420
And of course there is that question, do I really want to do it?

478
00:46:33,282 --> 00:46:40,001
Do I really, really want to take three, at that time it was just three years, take three years out to do a bit of meditation?

479
00:46:40,775 --> 00:46:48,244
And because of that, actually, what you're saying there is that, you know, sometimes in a choice, and I have found myself in big choices like that, you really want to do both.

480
00:46:48,684 --> 00:46:49,766
Yeah.

481
00:46:49,806 --> 00:46:51,027
Yeah, that's it.

482
00:46:51,047 --> 00:46:52,690
And that's because of conditioning.

483
00:46:52,710 --> 00:46:53,251
It is.

484
00:46:53,271 --> 00:46:55,273
You just said it right, the attachment.

485
00:46:55,393 --> 00:46:57,115
Yeah, you want your cake and to eat it.

486
00:46:57,135 --> 00:46:59,960
Yeah, absolutely, yeah.

487
00:46:59,980 --> 00:47:01,762
Was that a clue for the cup tea?

488
00:47:03,364 --> 00:47:04,925
Sounds like it.

489
00:47:08,331 --> 00:47:11,074
Sorry, he had the last of the cake.

490
00:47:11,235 --> 00:47:12,215
I had the last of the cake.

491
00:47:12,556 --> 00:47:21,206
If you're fairly well enlightened, you don't have to worry about making choices that come to you naturally.

492
00:47:21,226 --> 00:47:37,005
I would, who can guess what the Buddha's mind is like, but I can't imagine him worrying about a decision.

493
00:47:38,452 --> 00:47:39,213
It wouldn't make sense.

494
00:47:41,996 --> 00:47:45,641
So are you saying you don't need to go through that two years of turmoil and...

495
00:47:46,081 --> 00:47:46,702
I know you do.

496
00:47:46,983 --> 00:47:48,344
You still have to go through it.

497
00:47:48,644 --> 00:47:49,085
Yeah, yeah.

498
00:47:49,106 --> 00:47:50,967
Because that's the measure of our delusion.

499
00:47:52,809 --> 00:47:53,972
You have to work through it, yeah.

500
00:47:53,992 --> 00:47:55,072
Sometimes it is painful.

501
00:47:56,795 --> 00:47:57,396
But if you...

502
00:47:57,416 --> 00:48:04,764
I remember my sister went, two years, I think she took three years to decide to marry this poor bloke.

503
00:48:05,655 --> 00:48:09,041
who was certain after about a month of needing her, you know.

504
00:48:09,862 --> 00:48:10,702
Kept waiting about her.

505
00:48:13,606 --> 00:48:17,052
I mean, for her, of course, I mean, she was then a strong Catholic.

506
00:48:17,092 --> 00:48:22,259
I mean, it was a real decision because, you know, you presume it's going to last the rest of your life, you know.

507
00:48:27,005 --> 00:48:27,686
It was a good decision.

508
00:48:29,268 --> 00:48:30,369
She's all right, yeah.

509
00:48:32,552 --> 00:48:34,195
When I was trying to decide...

510
00:48:34,597 --> 00:48:37,599
in France and we had always had the ambition to come back and live in Ireland.

511
00:48:39,121 --> 00:48:43,025
And we worked and worked and saved and everything.

512
00:48:43,045 --> 00:48:44,847
And we had so many good reasons for coming back.

513
00:48:44,867 --> 00:48:46,469
There were so many good reasons.

514
00:48:47,530 --> 00:48:53,637
And then when we fixed the date about two years before we did come, I began to question the reasons.

515
00:48:53,777 --> 00:48:54,958
I was excited anyway.

516
00:48:55,280 --> 00:48:58,842
And I found myself, I found that every one of them was in bad.

517
00:48:59,704 --> 00:49:02,166
I wasn't worth coming back to Ireland for.

518
00:49:02,286 --> 00:49:03,068
But I stayed where I am.

519
00:49:04,313 --> 00:49:09,420
And then we had to, but we went through all the motions of putting the house up for sale and things like this.

520
00:49:09,440 --> 00:49:14,188
And the day came when we had to say, yes, I know what we're selling the house.

521
00:49:15,550 --> 00:49:21,260
And I had about half an hour to think about it.

522
00:49:21,280 --> 00:49:22,442
And I walked up here on the road.

523
00:49:23,664 --> 00:49:25,166
There were no reasons to come back.

524
00:49:25,186 --> 00:49:26,588
Why go through all that trouble?

525
00:49:27,590 --> 00:49:30,894
And then all of a sudden, brightness came into my life.

526
00:49:31,297 --> 00:49:33,599
Ireland, for me, is brightness.

527
00:49:34,699 --> 00:49:36,041
Illuminosity.

528
00:49:36,661 --> 00:49:39,204
I never thought of that before.

529
00:49:39,224 --> 00:49:43,048
And that became a valid reason for going back and it has proven true.

530
00:49:43,148 --> 00:49:46,512
Even for my children, they speak in the same terms.

531
00:49:46,532 --> 00:49:47,432
Where did that come from?

532
00:49:48,353 --> 00:49:54,940
Well, you know, eventually, the truth comes forth.

533
00:49:54,960 --> 00:49:55,981
It was a thing I didn't look for.

534
00:49:56,302 --> 00:49:57,844
I don't know.

535
00:49:58,447 --> 00:50:06,577
I mean, if you look at all these great spiritual leaders, they all go through that huge business.

536
00:50:07,577 --> 00:50:19,289
Christ in the desert, the Buddha in his desperation getting his little pot of rice pudding and then deciding that he was going to ascend to the tree and die or make it.

537
00:50:19,309 --> 00:50:21,532
And he's there in total confusion.

538
00:50:22,273 --> 00:50:24,434
He's sitting by the roadside wondering what the hell he's going to do.

539
00:50:25,115 --> 00:50:27,038
He's tried everything, getting nowhere.

540
00:50:28,030 --> 00:50:31,775
I put it all down the rice pudding, of course.

541
00:50:31,795 --> 00:50:34,000
And just in that moment, the light comes.

542
00:50:34,059 --> 00:50:40,150
He remembers this point in childhood and the way he was watching his father doing the ploughing ceremony.

543
00:50:40,170 --> 00:50:41,132
And that gave him the clue.

544
00:50:43,715 --> 00:50:52,992
It's only in those moments of catastrophe, the break, it's like, you know, what's that theory in evolution of the stick?

545
00:50:53,612 --> 00:50:54,293
two forms.

546
00:50:55,576 --> 00:50:57,018
Do you know what I mean?

547
00:50:57,039 --> 00:50:58,601
I can't remember that.

548
00:50:58,981 --> 00:51:00,123
If you remember it, will you tell me?

549
00:51:01,284 --> 00:51:05,532
Because it's exactly what happens in the spiritual life or in any form.

550
00:51:06,012 --> 00:51:09,518
You're bending the stick and you're bending it and the more you bend it, there's more resistance.

551
00:51:10,139 --> 00:51:11,221
More resistance, more pain.

552
00:51:11,280 --> 00:51:13,625
Then suddenly snap and you've got a different state.

553
00:51:13,644 --> 00:51:14,726
You've got two sticks.

554
00:51:15,836 --> 00:51:19,643
And that's, generally speaking, how we work spiritually.

555
00:51:19,902 --> 00:51:21,326
You just keep working and working.

556
00:51:21,606 --> 00:51:26,273
And it's just at the point of its most intense pain that the snap comes.

557
00:51:27,554 --> 00:51:29,097
And it's often where people give up.

558
00:51:29,117 --> 00:51:29,798
This is the problem.

559
00:51:32,262 --> 00:51:39,112
Yeah, and isn't that then important, this point to remember, to stay with the wish we make?

560
00:51:39,132 --> 00:51:40,175
Where do I want to go?

561
00:51:40,195 --> 00:51:43,380
In times like that, and the more...

562
00:51:43,478 --> 00:52:01,858
the more intense it becomes, the more it's important to remember this wish again and again and to work against the ingrained habits which always come back and the stronger the possibility at this point for change, the stronger is also the counter power.

563
00:52:02,197 --> 00:52:05,681
And then to stick with this wish and to remember, remember, remember.

564
00:52:06,222 --> 00:52:06,483
That's right.

565
00:52:08,083 --> 00:52:13,349
That's symbolized in the life of the Buddha, the attack of Nara, the armies of Nara came bursting upon him, you see.

566
00:52:17,278 --> 00:52:18,059
With cups of tea.

567
00:52:33,603 --> 00:52:35,385
We are very silent, thank you very much.

568
00:52:36,166 --> 00:52:42,275
Can I say something?

569
00:52:43,137 --> 00:52:46,121
Why does it have to all be so agonizing?

570
00:52:48,447 --> 00:52:53,034
Well, for some people it... No, we're not simple people, basically.

571
00:52:53,074 --> 00:52:54,155
You know, for some people it isn't.

572
00:52:54,456 --> 00:52:57,742
I mean, like, you know, I've just run this retreat at Sunyata.

573
00:52:57,762 --> 00:53:00,427
It was about 17-odd people, 18 people.

574
00:53:01,327 --> 00:53:06,356
And if you'd have talked to most of them, it was agony, it was painful and all that, right?

575
00:53:06,376 --> 00:53:10,963
But there was one on that retreat who was blissed out all the time.

576
00:53:10,983 --> 00:53:13,407
She was in seventh heaven every time she sat.

